<font color="#FF0000">ED, LZ SECURED DROP IN 4 A CUP</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 21  2:30:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It was laughter; our joking around that kept us sane in Nam.<br>
We faced and played with death and at times, I believed death feared us more then life.<br>
If we had not joked around, I believe many of us would not have made it back.<br><br>
But, Ed I didn't know those were jokes! or humor you were writing. I wish you would have told me. <br>
Sometimes you remind me of Marty. Did I ever tell you about Marty?<br><br>
Marty, well he was a grunt. A grunt in 3rd squad who used to come around and hang out with guns (m-60 machine gunners, for you Army, Air Force and Coast Guard personal, by the way my daughter just told me that ARMY stands for Aren't Really Men Yet).<br><br>
Anyways, Marty went and asked his squad leader if he could transfer over to guns and his squad leader rimmed him up and down. Figured Marty wanted to come over to guns because we got away with a whole lot of things and if he came over Marty would probably be killed. <br><br>
Guns were known for always partying and no one ever knew where we were. I didn't know who was in charge of guns for months. Funny our lieutenant did not know he was in charge of us, until I told him at our reunion in February. <br>
He though we were attached to a special weapons platoon, which was the normal way things were done, except in Nam. No one told him differently and we certainly were not about to.<br>
 <br>
When I first got there guns didn't stand watch at night. Our hooch was sandwiched in between two squads and as their vision covered our location and Arty was directly behind us, we just didn't bother standing watch. I never asked Bro about it and he never bothered to tell me. We never got up for breakfast and were always trading and going into DaNang for one thing or another. If a gun team was needed who ever was available just went.<br><br>
Well, Marty did come over and each time we went out Marty always gave me his personal belongings, he felt he might not make it back so I would mail his stuff back home for him. I figured I had to make it back because I had all of Marty's stuff to mail so I was not going to get killed. Of course, I always asked Marty if he was killed, if I could keep his camera. <br><br>
Marty, tried all he could to belong in guns, we had accepted him right from the start but never bothered to tell him. Told him we kept him around cause he made a great cup of hot chocalate or coffee. He was however, the glue that held us together. <br><br>
One day while trying to clean the .45 pistol, Marty accidentally shot a hole through a pile of Jones .45 records. Marty felt for sure that he would be booted out of guns, but you see Marty liked to carry the gun so Jones wasn't about to get rid of him, but of course Jones never told Marty that. In Nam Marty and I would always be in competition with each other. We used to practice single shooting the gun into the river. We would call in illumination so that we could shoot the flare out of the sky. In this manner we shot up hundreds and thousands of rounds just playing around. Little did we realize all that, was practice for the combat that was to come later. Marty today is the closest friend I have.<br><br>
He can be however at times a bit off the wall. When we were in San Antonio, Marty drank a couple of beers; Marty does not drink so you can imagine what happened. Soon he was hollering at boats on the Riverwalk and irritating a table full of about 12 Air Force cadets who were drinking beer next to us. When I got up to leave, I told a couple of them to take care of Marty, as he had been the best machine gunner in Nam. By the time I came around to pay the tab, all 12 flyboys were singing and tapping the Marine Corps song for Marty and buying him another beer.  Marty grows on people like that. <br><br>
Ed, you're just like Marty to me, except you have six times as many ribbons, medals, and many more shinny little buttons then he does. All your titles also start with &quot;Special&quot; forces this or that and Marty's does not. He was just a grunt and a wannabe gunner. But I never told him that gooks liked shooting at machine gunners, he just figured he was popular and I never bothered to tell him differently.<br>
 When Marty came back home, he became a hippie, and a great photographer. Then he married a beautiful and wonderful women, today he runs his own construction company and we often talk during the week.  <br>
We played around a lot in Nam, that kept us sane and I noticed that we did the same at the San Antonio reunion. But it was Marty that made that reunion special. <br><br>
Ed its reading what you post that makes this dialog special, you and guys like silent warrior remind me of a lot of guys that bailed us out of very many tight situations. Yes, I hate to admit it but on one of our darkest days when we had just about ran out of ammo and the birddog hanging around had already called in everyone and their brother from as close and as faraway as possible to drop their loads for us, just when there was no one else around and no further help around and we had already prepared our gasmarks for theattack that was to come,  Army (yes, Army) attack chopper showed up and asked if he could help (November 21st 1967). He saved our necks that day and kept the gooks off our front door long enough for reinforcements to arrive, gee, those were great memories. <br>

<p><code>-- LZ Secured  (SparrowHawk) </code><p>


